**Fibonacci Series using Recursion in C++**
=====================================================

### Overview

The Fibonacci series is a series of numbers where a number is the addition of the last two numbers, usually starting with 0 and 1.

### Code

```cpp
#include <iostream>

/**
 * Function to calculate the nth Fibonacci number using recursion.
 *
 * @param n The position of the Fibonacci number to calculate.
 * @return The nth Fibonacci number.
 */
int fibonacci(int n) {
    if (n <= 0) {
        // Base case: Fibonacci of 0 is 0
        return 0;
    } else if (n == 1) {
        // Base case: Fibonacci of 1 is 1
        return 1;
    } else {
        // Recursive case: Fibonacci of n is the sum of Fibonacci of (n-1) and (n-2)
        return fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2);
    }
}

int main() {
    int n;
    std::cout << "Enter the position of the Fibonacci number: ";
    std::cin >> n;

    if (n < 0) {
        std::cout << "Error: n should be a non-negative integer." << std::endl;
    } else {
        int result = fibonacci(n);
        std::cout << "Fibonacci number at position " << n << " is: " << result << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

### Explanation

This C++ program uses recursion to calculate the nth Fibonacci number. The `fibonacci` function takes an integer `n` as input and returns the corresponding Fibonacci number. The base cases are when `n` is 0 or 1, in which case the function returns 0 or 1, respectively. For any other value of `n`, the function calls itself with `n-1` and `n-2` and returns the sum of the results.

### Example Use Case

When you run the program, it will ask you to enter the position of the Fibonacci number you want to calculate. For example, if you enter 5, the program will output the 5th Fibonacci number, which is 3.

### Note

Please note that this recursive implementation has an exponential time complexity due to the repeated calculation of the same sub-problems. For larger values of `n`, this can be inefficient. A more efficient solution would use dynamic programming or memoization to store and reuse previously calculated values.

**Sequence of Numbers using Recursion in C++**
=====================================================

### Overview

The sequence of numbers is defined as follows:

* The first three numbers are 0, -1, -1.
* Each subsequent number is the sum of the previous three numbers.

### Code

```cpp
#include <iostream>

/**
 * Function to calculate the nth number in the sequence using recursion.
 *
 * @param n The position of the number in the sequence to calculate.
 * @param prev1 The first of the previous three numbers.
 * @param prev2 The second of the previous three numbers.
 * @param prev3 The third of the previous three numbers.
 * @return The nth number in the sequence.
 */
int sequence(int n, int prev1 = 0, int prev2 = -1, int prev3 = -1) {
    if (n <= 0) {
        // Base case: if n is less than or equal to 0, return 0
        return 0;
    } else if (n == 1) {
        // Base case: if n is 1, return the first number in the sequence
        return 0;
    } else if (n == 2) {
        // Base case: if n is 2, return the second number in the sequence
        return -1;
    } else if (n == 3) {
        // Base case: if n is 3, return the third number in the sequence
        return -1;
    } else {
        // Recursive case: return the sum of the previous three numbers
        return sequence(n - 1, prev2, prev3, prev1 + prev2 + prev3);
    }
}

int main() {
    int n;
    std::cout << "Enter the position of the number in the sequence: ";
    std::cin >> n;

    if (n < 0) {
        std::cout << "Error: n should be a non-negative integer." << std::endl;
    } else {
        int result = sequence(n);
        std::cout << "The " << n << "th number in the sequence is: " << result << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

### Explanation

This C++ program uses recursion to calculate the nth number in the sequence. The `sequence` function takes four parameters: `n` (the position of the number to calculate), and the previous three numbers in the sequence (`prev1`, `prev2`, and `prev3`). The base cases are when `n` is less than or equal to 0 (in which case the function returns 0), or when `n` is 1, 2, or 3 (in which case the function returns the corresponding initial numbers in the sequence). For any other value of `n`, the function calls itself with the previous three numbers and returns the sum of the previous three numbers.

### Example Use Case

When you run the program, it will ask you to enter the position of the number in the sequence you want to calculate. For example, if you enter 5, the program will output the 5th number in the sequence.

### Note

Please note that this recursive implementation has an exponential time complexity due to the repeated calculation of the same sub-problems. For larger values of `n`, this can be inefficient. A more efficient solution would use dynamic programming or memoization to store and reuse previously calculated values.

